Hype Frog governance baseline (Wave 2+):

1) Architecture ownership is strict.
- Foundations: `src/hype_frog/core/` and shared `config`.
- Engines: `src/hype_frog/crawler/`, `src/hype_frog/pipeline/`, `src/hype_frog/reporter/`.
- Flows: `src/hype_frog/orchestration/`.
- Keep logic in owning layer; do not collapse modules into new junk-drawer helpers.

2) Typed chain-of-trust is mandatory.
- Runtime row/state payloads must validate through Pydantic models in `src/hype_frog/core/models.py`.
- New public APIs require explicit type hints.
- Prefer additive keys over renames/removals for established payload contracts.

3) Logic and layout separation is mandatory.
- Business/scoring logic belongs in crawler/pipeline/rules modules.
- Workbook layout, style, TOC, and view-state rules belong in reporter modules.
- Reporter must treat upstream payload dictionaries as read-only.

4) Atomic changes and scope control.
- Keep diffs small and reviewable.
- If work spans more than 3 files, require explicit user approval unless already provided in-thread.
- Avoid mass rewrites or deletion of legacy material without direct request.

5) Runtime safety and observability.
- Keep async paths non-blocking.
- Use bounded retries/backoff for network operations.
- Use shared logging helpers; no ad hoc `print()` telemetry in runtime modules.

6) Excel integrity rules are non-negotiable.
- Sanitize string values for workbook safety/injection prevention.
- Preserve ghost-pane/view-state guardrails and TOC-to-tab consistency.
- Keep Content Optimisation Hub action semantics aligned with existing conditional formatting rules.

7) Toolchain policy.
- Use `uv` only: `uv add`, `uv sync`, `uv run`.
- Do not use `pip`, `pip freeze`, or `python -m venv`.
- Treat `uv.lock` as the dependency source of truth.

8) Language and docs policy.
- User-facing copy and workbook text use British English.
- Keep `README.md`, `.cursor/rules/*.mdc`, and `docs/*.md` aligned whenever architecture/contracts change.
